President Obama spoke with Governor Pat McCrory of North Carolina to discuss the response to Hurricane Matthew and the flooding in the state. The President signed a major disaster declaration for North Carolina and reiterated the need for federal resources to assist the impacted states. He expressed his condolences for those who lost their lives and urged those in the potential path of the flooding to listen to local officials. The President also received a briefing from Lisa Monaco, Assistant to the President for Homeland Security and Counterterrorism, on the impacts of Hurricane Matthew and the ongoing federal response and recovery efforts. FEMA, Coast Guard, Army Corps of Engineers, and National Park Service responders are involved in recovery efforts, including thousands of water rescues. Over 1,500 FEMA staff are deployed to impacted states, and prepositioned commodities such as meals, water, and blankets have been distributed. The President will continue to be updated on the response.